            "content": [
              {
                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "Here are several **fresh AI headlines and themes** showing up in the latest reporting (early March 2026):\n\n- **AI and the military: tensions over safety controls**\n  - Coverage highlights a growing divide between AI labs and defense agencies about whether advanced models should have **unrestricted military capabilities** versus enforced safety limitations—one prominent storyline centers on a reported Pentagon–Anthropic conflict over safety restrictions and access terms.【6:1†source】\n\n- **“Agentic AI” moves from demos into real deployments (and real failure modes)**\n  - Industry digests describe a shift from pure “capability racing” to whether AI agents can be **reliable in production**, plus whether the **economics (pricing, subscriptions, enterprise deals)** are sustainable as vendors monetize more aggressively.【6:0†source】\n\n- **Legal backlash continues: AI-hallucinated citations in court filings**\n  - A Connecticut Supreme Court matter drew attention after lawyers admitted generative AI produced **fabricated citations/quotes** in a brief—another high-profile example of why courts and bar associations are pushing stricter verification expectations.【6:0†source】\n\n- **Consumer AI expands into shopping/product research**\n  - Meta is reported to be testing an AI “shopping research” capability in its chatbot, signaling continued competition with assistants that do product discovery and comparisons.【6:0†source】\n\nIf you tell me what you mean by “latest” (past 24 hours vs. past week) and what angle you care about (policy, big labs, chips, startups, research breakthroughs), I can narrow this to the most relevant items.",
